Warning: super emergency solution, if you are okay with possibly ruining the board. Also pretty intricate.
You can try to jam the pins by sticking something thin that fits in every hole on -one- side between the board and the pins. A toothpick end if the gap is big enough or some paper (foil is pretty good if you are careful not to make new connections, disregard one side rule in this case). If you managed to balance everything out so that every pin touches metal of its hole reliably, superglue every hole (don't apply too much so it doesn't go on other components). Then you have to be very careful inserting it in as superglue is brittle, maybe help it go in by gently applying pressure to all the pins from the top. Then you never disconnect it if you want it working, assume first disconnect will break it.
If you are not in immediate need of a bodge job just buy a cheapo chinese soldering iron, they are very good for the price.', 'time': 1670731589, 'resto': 1292877}, {'no': 1292955, 'now': '12/11/22(Sun)00:39:21', 'name': 'Anonymous', 'com': '>>1292877

com:
Decode this: ENT1yWWhLL-Qz9mK

A Twitter snowflake ID is a 64-bit binary number, with 41 bits representing a timestamp, 10 bits representing a machine ID, and 12 bits representing a per-machine sequence number. The snowflake ID is generally serialized in decimal format and is used in the post URL.

For example,
https://twitter.com/i/status/1581674019991916545
Decoding 1581674019991916545:
{'creation_time_milliseconds': 1665935447105,
'datacenter_id': 10,
'machine_id': 337,
'sequence_id': 1,
'server_id': 17}

The filename of a Twitter photo also contains a base64-encoded snowflake ID. This can be decoded into a regular snowflake ID, although it contains three "extra" unknown bytes.
For example,
https://pbs.twimg.com/media/FdMR2WDaMAMPt2q?format=jpg
FdMR2WDaMAMPt2q -> 1572620320212922371

It is unknown if the filename of a Twitter video also contains a snowflake ID. You can see the URL contains it, but any off-platform video would would only contain the file name.
For example,
https://video.twimg.com/ext_tw_video/1564378065198882816/pu/vid/960x720/ENT1yWWhLL-Qz9mK.mp4

How would "ENT1yWWhLL-Qz9mK" be decoded into a snowflake, if it's possible?

Resources:
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Snowflake_ID
https://discord.com/developers/docs/reference#snowflakes (good visualizations, twitter uses another epoch)
https://docs.google.com/document/d/1xVrPoNutyqTdQ04DXBEZW4ZW4A5RAQW2he7qIpTmG-M/edit

last_replies:
[{'no': 1292861, 'now': '12/10/22(Sat)19:53:31', 'name': 'Anonymous', 'com': '>>1292860
https://99designs.com/blog/tips/ppi-vs-dpi-whats-the-difference/', 'time': 1670720011, 'resto': 1292860}, {'no': 1292878, 'now': '12/10/22(Sat)21:16:58', 'name': 'Anonymous', 'com': '>>1292860
It means that if you want to print a 6x4 photo your image is no more than 1800 x 1200 pixels ie 1800 pixels / 6 inches = 300 pixels/inch = 300ppi.

But if you were printing that photo as 12 x 8 it would be 1800 / 12 = 150 pixels per inch.

It's pixel dimension divided by length of desired print.

If you do this for height and width of photo and you get different number pixels per inch, the printer is doing to make you crop the image, which ever side had the higher ppi number is going to need to be shortened since printers usually won't add plain white borders automatically. You can either crop it yourself using some graphics editor, crop it in the kiosk machine or the website that will print the photo, or you can use a graphics program to add borders yourself to the too short dimension.', 'time': 1670725018, 'resto': 1292860}, {'no': 1292886, 'now': '12/10/22(Sat)21:38:48', 'name': 'Anonymous', 'com': '>>1292860

>I want to learn more kanji and thought of buying novels to read.

Before you go to more text only novels, You can go to websites that have both japanese and translated doujins and manga. You then get the convenience of reading the japanese version, translating it in your mind, and then comparing your translated understanding with the translated english version of doujin or manga. Because doujins and manga are panel and page-oriented, it is easy to find translated text and compare your translation accuracy to wht was already translated.

This kind of easy to perform comparison helps you learn katakana/hiragana and kanji translations faster.
